        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>[Down]</placeName>
                    <date>May 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1865</date>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>In case of my death, I desire that a yearly annuity of £50 be paid to J. Parslow for his faithful services &amp; friendship, as long as he may live; or in case of his becoming unfit for service.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>In case of my wifes sudden death, with no proper provision having been made for this annuity being paid, We desire our children to pay conjointly this annuity.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Ch. Darwin | Emma Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.1 yearly] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.1 £50] ‘£’ <hi rend="italic">above</hi> ‘50’ <hi rend="italic">in MS</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">2.1 having been made] <hi rend="italic">added</hi></note>
                </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3699.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Joseph Parslow</ref> was the butler at Down House; he began in CD’s service in Upper Gower Street, London, <hi rend="italic">circa</hi> 1840 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_994.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Browne 1995</ref>). Parslow retired in 1875 on a pension of £50 a year and the rent of his house, Home Cottage, Back Lane, Down (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2662.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1978</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">The document is folded in a small envelope bearing the words, ‘Memorandum | Annuity for J. Parslow | May 1865.’</note>
        </div>        
            
